# plan9port fork (dnjp)

The plan9port submodule lives at `plan9/modules/plan9port/`. It is a fork of
[9fans/plan9port](https://github.com/9fans/plan9port) maintained at
`origin/dnjp` (default branch). Upstream is `upstream/master`.

## Key locations

| Path | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/` | plan9port submodule root |
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/src/cmd/acme/` | Acme editor source |
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/src/cmd/devdraw/` | Display server (NSApplication process on macOS) |
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/src/cmd/plumb/` | Plumber source |
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/src/cmd/9term/` | 9term terminal and `win` (Acme terminal window) source |
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/src/libdraw/` | Drawing library (spawns devdraw) |
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/mac/` | macOS app bundles and LaunchAgent daemons |
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/bin/` | Shell scripts: `editinacme`, `plumb-edit`, `p9p-open`, `acme` wrapper, `9term` wrapper |
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/plumb/macos` | Fallback rules routing files to native macOS apps via `p9p-open` |
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/tests/plumb/` | Automated plumbing routing tests |
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/plumb/basic` | Default plumbing rules |
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/shell/` | Shell environment templates (`*.sh.in` → `*.sh` via SETUP) |
| `plan9/modules/plan9port/SETUP` | One-shot install script |
| `~/lib/rules` | User's personal ruler rule file |

## Build system

- Uses `mk` (plan9port's make). Build targets: `mk all`, `mk install`.
- Binaries install to `/usr/local/plan9/bin/`.
- On macOS, `mkmany` and `mkone` automatically `codesign --force --sign -` after install.
- To build acme: `cd src/cmd/acme && mk o.acme.bin` (local test binary).
- **Never use `sudo cp` to install binaries** — use `mk install` which also codesigns.

## macOS app bundles

`devdraw` is the actual `NSApplication` process (owns Dock icon, menu bar).
Each app bundle (`Acme.app`, `9term.app`, `Sam.app`) contains a copy of
`devdraw` in `Contents/MacOS/`. The launcher script sets `DEVDRAW=$(dirname "$0")/devdraw`
so libdraw execs the bundle-internal copy, giving macOS the correct icon and name.
`devdraw`'s `applicationDidFinishLaunching` reads `CFBundleName` and
`CFBundleIconFile` from `[NSBundle mainBundle]` to set the menu title and icon.
`mk apps` (in `mac/`) copies the bundles and the devdraw binary to `/Applications`.

**After `mk apps`, always re-sign with `--deep`:**
```sh
codesign --force --deep --sign - /Applications/Acme.app
```
Copying `devdraw` into the bundle invalidates the signature. `--deep` is required
to re-seal the entire bundle; signing only the top-level or only the binary causes
macOS to `SIGKILL` the process at launch.

### Single-process multi-window model

Each app bundle runs a single long-lived `devdraw` process. All windows live as
`NSWindow` instances inside that one process. `devdraw` acts as a 9P server;
clients connect via Unix socket using `$wsysid`. This gives a single Dock icon,
single menu bar, and native Cmd+` window cycling.

### Window / DrawView lifecycle — CRITICAL

`DrawView` owns each window's drawing surface. Two teardown paths:

**Path A — User closes window**: `windowWillClose:` sets `clientGone=YES`,
sets `self.win=nil` (releases ARC retain while AppKit still holds its own),
then closes the client socket fd. `serveproc` sees EOF → `rpc_clientgone` →
main thread cleanup.

**Path B — Client exits**: `serveproc` EOF → `rpc_clientgone` → main thread →
`[view.win orderOut:nil]` → `view.win=nil`.

**`isReleasedWhenClosed=NO` is mandatory.** `NSWindow` defaults to
`isReleasedWhenClosed=YES` — AppKit fires an extra `-release` on close. Combined
with `DrawView.win` being a `retain` property, this causes a double-free crash
(`*** -[NSWindow release]: message sent to deallocated instance`). Always set
`[win setReleasedWhenClosed:NO]` when creating windows in `mac-screen.m`.

### viewRegistry

Maps raw `void*` client view pointers to `CFRetain`'d `DrawView` references so
background libthread threads can safely look up views. Rules:
- `viewRegistry_add`: `CFRetain`s the view (registry owns +1).
- `viewRegistry_getref`: returns +1 ref; caller must `__bridge_transfer` inside
  a `dispatch_async` block on the main thread inside `@autoreleasepool`.
- `viewRegistry_remove`: `CFRelease`s registry's +1. Main thread only, after
  `clientGone` is set.

### Launcher scripts

Bundle launcher scripts (`Contents/MacOS/acme` etc.) must set `PLAN9` and
`export PATH="$PLAN9/bin:$PATH"` — Dock-launched apps inherit a minimal `PATH`
that doesn't include plan9port binaries.

`Plumb.app`'s launcher (`Contents/MacOS/plumb`) calls `macargv` to receive
Finder file paths, then passes each to `plumb` directly. The plumber routes
files to acme, Preview, QuickTime, etc. based on `~/lib/plumbing`. Upstream's
`bin/macedit` (which forced all files to the editor) is not used in this fork —
see `mac/MacOS.md` for the full explanation.

## Plumbing

- Uses `plumb client $editor` (upstream pattern). `$editor=plumb-edit` is set in `~/lib/plumbing`.
- `plumb to edit` must be a **standalone top-level declaration** — required because `plumb client`
  only registers the port when a client connects; the plumber needs it declared up-front.
- A ruleset may have at most one `plumb to X` and one `plumb start`/`plumb client`.
  Having two `plumb to` lines in one ruleset causes "too many ports" parse error.
- **`include macos` placement**: must come **before** the `(.+?)` editor catch-all in
  `~/lib/plumbing`. That catch-all matches any existing file, so macos rules must fire first.
- **Filename regexes**: use `.+` guards (not restrictive character classes) so filenames with
  spaces, braces, etc. match. `arg isfile $0` verifies existence.
- **`buildargv` space splitting**: `$file` in `plumb start` is split on spaces into multiple
  argv elements. Use `p9p-open` instead of `open` directly — it reassembles the parts.
- **Single quotes ≠ shell quoting**: `'$file'` in a plumber rule prevents `$file` expansion
  entirely (plumber strips quotes but doesn't expand inside them). Use bare `$file`.
- **`p9p-open`**: wrapper in `bin/p9p-open`, installed to `$PLAN9/bin/p9p-open` by `mk apps`.
  Called as `plumb start p9p-open -b <bundleID> $file` in `plumb/macos`.
- After editing `~/lib/plumbing`: reload with `cat ~/lib/plumbing | 9p write plumb/rules`.
- After editing `plumb/basic` or `plumb/macos`: `sudo install -m644 plumb/basic $PLAN9/plumb/basic`
  then reload rules.
- **Test routing**: `cd tests/plumb && bash run-tests` — verifies PDF→Preview, WAV→QuickTime,
  source files→editor, etc. without opening actual apps (uses `p9p-open`'s test hook).

## editinacme

`bin/editinacme` is used as `$EDITOR` (e.g. for `git commit`). Key design:
- Starts `acme` if not running; waits for `9p stat acme` (not `plumb/edit`, which always exists).
- Starts `9p read acme/log` into a fifo **before** sending `plumb -d edit $file` to avoid missing the `del` event.
- Uses a second done-fifo so awk signals completion without closing the log pipe prematurely.
- Kills background processes with `kill $pids | rc` (plan9port `kill` prints commands; pipe to `rc` executes them).

## Ruler

The ruler daemon applies per-window directives (font, tabstop, etc.) in acme.
- Rules live in `~/lib/rules`.
- `rulerdebug=1` enables verbose logging in acme.
- `rulerprefont(w)` is called before `textload` to set the font before the frame is filled, avoiding a re-render flash.
- Acme's custom 64-entry LRU subfont cache (`src/cmd/acme/cache.c`) overrides libdraw's single-entry cache to prevent thrashing when variable and fixed fonts are both in use.

## Acme file names (contracted vs expanded)

Acme keeps two versions of a file path on `File`:
- `File.name` / `File.nname`: **display name** (usually contracted, e.g. `~/.profile`)
- `File.ename` / `File.nename`: **external name** (expanded, e.g. `/Users/daniel/.profile`)

Use the contracted form for UI (row/window/tag). Use the expanded form for logs and 9P (`acme/log`, `acme/index`, `.../tag`) and for filesystem operations like `Put`.

## Shell environment templates

Files ending in `.sh.in`, `.fish.in`, `.rc.in` in `shell/` are templates.
`SETUP` processes them with `sed "s|/usr/local/plan9|$PLAN9|g"` and installs via
`mk install` (no sudo — `/usr/local/plan9` is user-owned). **Edit the `.in`
files, never the generated ones.**

**PATH ordering**: `plan9.sh` must be sourced **last** in `~/.profile`, after
homebrew, asdf, go, tfenv, etc. have run. Those tools prepend to `PATH`; if
`plan9.sh` runs first they will bury `$PLAN9/bin`. The `case ":${PATH}:"` guard
in `plan9.sh` only skips the prepend if `$PLAN9/bin` is already present — it
does not re-prepend if it was subsequently buried.

## 9term and win

### 9term key bindings (additions over upstream)

| Key | Action |
|-----|--------|
| Ctrl+C | Send interrupt (unconditional, even in raw mode) |
| Ctrl+D | Send EOT (unconditional, even in raw mode) |
| Ctrl+K | Delete from cursor to end of line |
| Ctrl+P | Previous command history entry |
| Ctrl+N | Next command history entry |
| Alt+Left/Right | Move cursor by word |
| Cmd+Left/Right | Move to start/end of line (stops at prompt boundary, like `^A`/`^E`) |
| Shift+Left/Right | Extend/shrink selection by one character |
| Shift+Alt+Left/Right | Extend/shrink selection by one word |
| Shift+Cmd+Left/Right | Extend/shrink selection to start/end of line |
| Button 3 (right-click) | Plumb word under pointer (or current selection) |

### 9term internals

- `Window.cursoratq1`: tracks which end of the selection is the moving cursor for shift-selection. Reset to 0 on plain left/right moves.
- `Window.hist[]` / `Window.histidx`: per-window ring buffer (256 entries). `histidx == -1` means not browsing. `histpending` saves the live input while browsing.
- `Kscrolloneup`/`Kscrollonedown` in `dat.h` are at `KF|0x26`/`KF|0x27` (not `0x20`/`0x21` which conflict with `keyboard.h`'s `Kshiftaltright`/`Kcmdleft`).
- `-f fixfont`: monospace font for terminal text. `-F varfont`: proportional font for button-2 menus.

### win internals

`win` is an Acme client (`src/cmd/9term/win.c`). It communicates via Acme's 9P event protocol — it never sees raw key codes. Keyboard input arrives as `'K'` `'I'` events with the character already inserted into the Acme body.

**Critical**: when `win` intercepts a `'K'` `'I'` event and `break`s before calling `type()`, `ntyper`/`ntypeb` do not yet reflect the inserted character, but the Acme body does. Before calling `histreplace`, always do:
```c
ntyper += e.nr;
ntypeb += e.nb;
```
This makes the delete range `[q.p, q.p+ntyper)` cover the inserted control character so `histreplace` wipes it cleanly.

History uses Ctrl+P/Ctrl+N (plain control characters that Acme passes through). Shift+Up/Down and other special keys are intercepted by Acme for text selection before `win` sees them.

